<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-06-24T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-06-24T12:00:00-05:00" n="84" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d84">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/18: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-06-24T13:00:00-04:00">June 24, 1929—1
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>154. Your No. 166, June 22, 1 p.m. I agree with your view that it would
                            be wise to keep the Japanese Ambassador closely informed with regard to
                            the subject matter of any conferences which you and Gibson may have with
                            the British, but I do not think that he should be present personally in
                            any such conversations as otherwise the rumor might arise that a
                            conference was already under way to the exclusion of France and
                            Italy.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
